2 Data

  • Stat2Data package: Link
    • Whickham2 dataset: Mortality data, smoking status, and age for \(n = 1314\) women in Whickham, England
      • Outcome: Status at 20-year follow-up (Alive or Dead)
      • Smoker: Smoker at baseline? (No or Yes)
      • Age: Age (in years at baseline)
      • AgeGroup: Age group (18-64 or 65+)
      • Alive: Numeric code for Outcome (1 = alive or 0 = dead)
    • Described here: Appleton, D. R., French, J. M., and Vanderpump, M.P. (1996), Ignoring a Covariate: An Example of Simpsonâs Paradox, The American Statistician, 50, 340-341.

2.1 AgeGroup3: Create a 3 category variable from Age

  • Create a new variable called AgeGroup3 based on Age
    • AgeGroup3 = 1 if Age is 18 to 40
    • AgeGroup3 = 2 if Age is 41 to 64
    • AgeGroup3 = 3 if Age otherwise (i.e., 65+)
Whickham2 <- Whickham2 %>%
    mutate(AgeGroup3 = ifelse(Age %in% 18:40, 1,
           ifelse(Age %in% 41:64, 2, 3)))
head(Whickham2)
  Outcome Smoker Age AgeGroup Alive AgeGroup3
1   Alive    Yes  23    18-64     1         1
2   Alive    Yes  18    18-64     1         1
3    Dead    Yes  71      65+     0         3
4   Alive     No  67      65+     1         3
5   Alive     No  64    18-64     1         2
6   Alive    Yes  38    18-64     1         1

3.2 Residuals

  • Overall \(\chi^2\) is significant (from above)
Age3_Alive_chi2

    Pearson's Chi-squared test

data:  Age3_Alive
X-squared = 565.67, df = 2, p-value < 0.00000000000000022
  • Observed values from \(\chi^2\) test (matches above)
Age3_Alive_chi2$observed
          Alive
AgeGroup   Dead Alive
  18 to 40   19   521
  41 to 64  141   390
  65+       209    34
  • Expected values from \(\chi^2\) test (matches above)
Age3_Alive_chi2$expected
          Alive
AgeGroup        Dead    Alive
  18 to 40 151.64384 388.3562
  41 to 64 149.11644 381.8836
  65+       68.23973 174.7603
  • Raw residuals: observed - expected = \(n_{ij} - \hat{\mu}_{ij}\)
    • Sort of a pattern, but doesnât fully account for different marginal values
      • i.e., There are 540 people who are 18 to 40, but only 243 people who are 65+
resids <- Age3_Alive_chi2$observed - Age3_Alive_chi2$expected
resids
          Alive
AgeGroup          Dead       Alive
  18 to 40 -132.643836  132.643836
  41 to 64   -8.116438    8.116438
  65+       140.760274 -140.760274
  • Standardized residuals: \(\frac{n_{ij} - \hat{\mu}_{ij}}{\sqrt{\hat{\mu}_{ij}(1-p_{i+})(1-p_{+j})}}\)
    • where \(\sqrt{\hat{\mu}_{ij}(1-p_{i+})(1-p_{+j})}\) is std error of raw residuals under \(H_0\)
    • and \(p_{i+} = n_{i+}/n\) and \(p_{+j} = n_{+j}/n\)
    • Account for the marginal values and variance of residuals
Age3_Alive_chi2$stdres
          Alive
AgeGroup         Dead      Alive
  18 to 40 -16.549454  16.549454
  41 to 64  -1.015316   1.015316
  65+       22.255953 -22.255953
  • Cut-off are \(\pm 2\)
    • 18 to 40 year olds have fewer dead (and more alive) than expected under independence
    • 65+ year olds have more dead (and fewer alive) than expected under independence

4.3.5 Another way to calculate frequencies and probabilties

  • This way is good for making plots
    • Itâs kind of a pain to get the values out of a table
    • And they donât play nice with e.g., ggplot2

4.3.5.1 Alive vs AgeGroup, conditional on Smoker

  • Line by line description:
    • Calculate the number of rows in the dataset (n)
    • Create a new dataset called Whickham2_freq1
      • Give it the Whickham2 dataset
    • Group the data by all three variables so all calculations will be within each combination of variables
      • i.e., a new variable will be within a cell, not for the whole sample
      • Order doesnât really matter, but I like Alive last (\(Y\))
    • summarize() reduces the dataset to fewer rows
      • And calculates a summary statistic, such as the count of the rows
      • This counts the number of 0s and 1s for each combination of AgeGroup and Smoker
    • ungroup() stops the grouping so we can calculate for the whole dataset again
    • Group the data by the two âpredictorsâ (not Alive) so all calculations will be within each combination of those two variables
    • mutate() creates new variables
      • prop is the number of 0s and 1s divided by the total n for that cell
      • totaln is the total number of observations in that cell
    • filter(Alive ==1) removes the Alive = 0 rows, leaving only the Alive = 1 rows
      • If you didnât do this, youâd have 2 rows for each cell of the table
      • Number of 0s, number of 1s
n <- nrow(Whickham2)
Whickham2_freq1 <- Whickham2 %>%
    group_by(AgeGroup, Smoker, Alive) %>%
    summarize(count = n()) %>%
    ungroup() %>%
    group_by(AgeGroup, Smoker) %>%
    mutate(prop = count/sum(count), 
           totaln = sum(count)) %>%
    filter(Alive == 1)
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'AgeGroup', 'Smoker'. You can override
using the `.groups` argument.
head(Whickham2_freq1)
# A tibble: 4 Ã 6
# Groups:   AgeGroup, Smoker [4]
  AgeGroup Smoker Alive count  prop totaln
  <fct>    <fct>  <int> <int> <dbl>  <int>
1 18-64    No         1   474 0.879    539
2 18-64    Yes        1   437 0.821    532
3 65+      No         1    28 0.145    193
4 65+      Yes        1     6 0.12      50

4.4 Plots

4.4.1 Conditional effect of AgeGroup, conditional on Smokerâ¦

  • The data are in Whickham2_freq1
  • The \(X\) variable is AgeGroup
  • The \(Y\) variable is prop
  • geom_point() adds points from the dataset and variables specified
  • geom_line() adds lines from the dataset and variables specified
  • ylim(0, 1) makes the \(Y\) axis go from 0 to 1
  • labs(y = "Proportion alive") changes the label for the \(Y\) axis
ggplot(data = Whickham2_freq1,
       aes(x = AgeGroup, y = prop)) +
    geom_point(aes(group = Smoker, color = Smoker)) +
    geom_line(aes(group = Smoker, color = Smoker)) +
    ylim(0, 1) +
    labs(y = "Proportion alive")

4.4.2 â¦plus marginal effect, ignoring Smoker

  • Only the last two âchunksâ are new
    • geom_point() adds points
      • From new dataset Whickham2_freq3
      • Same \(X\) and \(Y\) variables
      • group = 1 is to override the group = Smoker above
      • color = "black" and shape = "x" to change appearance of points
    • geom_line() adds a line
      • From new dataset Whickham2_freq3
      • Same \(X\) and \(Y\) variables
      • group = 1 is to override the group = Smoker above
      • color = "black" and linetype = "dashed" to change appearance of line
ggplot(data = data.frame(Whickham2_freq1),
       aes(x = AgeGroup, y = prop)) +
    geom_point(aes(group = Smoker, color = Smoker)) +
    geom_line(aes(group = Smoker, color = Smoker)) +
    ylim(0, 1) +
    labs(y = "Proportion alive") +
    geom_point(data = Whickham2_freq3, 
               aes(x = AgeGroup, y = prop, group = 1), 
               color = "black", shape = "x") +
    geom_line(data = Whickham2_freq3, 
              aes(x = AgeGroup, y = prop, group = 1),
              color = "black", linetype = "dashed")

4.4.3 Add an annotation, such as the total n that each point is based on

  • geom_text() adds text based on variable values
    • label = totaln uses the values in totaln as the labels
    • vjust = "outward" pushes the numbers off the points a bit
      • It doesnât always look great
ggplot(data = data.frame(Whickham2_freq1),
       aes(x = AgeGroup, y = prop)) +
    geom_point(aes(group = Smoker, color = Smoker)) +
    geom_line(aes(group = Smoker, color = Smoker)) +
    ylim(0, 1) +
    labs(y = "Proportion alive") +
    geom_point(data = Whickham2_freq3, 
               aes(x = AgeGroup, y = prop, group = 1), 
               color = "black", shape = "x") +
    geom_line(data = Whickham2_freq3, 
              aes(x = AgeGroup, y = prop, group = 1),
              color = "black", linetype = "dashed") +
    geom_text(aes(label = totaln), vjust = "outward")

4.4.4 Annotation option: Use ggrepel package and geom_text_repel()

  • This often does a better job at pushing labels off points without additional adjustments
    • Also has a ton of other options
ggplot(data = data.frame(Whickham2_freq1),
       aes(x = AgeGroup, y = prop)) +
    geom_point(aes(group = Smoker, color = Smoker)) +
    geom_line(aes(group = Smoker, color = Smoker)) +
    ylim(0, 1) +
    labs(y = "Proportion alive") +
    geom_point(data = Whickham2_freq3, 
               aes(x = AgeGroup, y = prop, group = 1), 
               color = "black", shape = "x") +
    geom_line(data = Whickham2_freq3, 
              aes(x = AgeGroup, y = prop, group = 1),
              color = "black", linetype = "dashed") +
    geom_text_repel(aes(label = totaln), vjust = "outward")
